messages.content:
‚ÄúHaha‚Ä¶ no. I won‚Äôt just bleed out. You won‚Äôt‚Ä¶ you‚Äôre not going to get out of *this* one‚Ä¶ just because everyone avoids you‚Ä¶‚Äù She stumbles forward, as if about to fall, and then transitions this into a roundhouse kick. It looks really cool, but doesn‚Äôt actually hurt like, at all. She misjudged the distance and it only grazed Voreverl. ‚ÄúNo one will care. Just another runaway to file missing, another loose end for this stupid burro‚Äîbureaucratic conspiracy to sweep up. This does *nothing* for you. It‚Äôs a confrontation about me, for my sake only, and that‚Äôll be my final revenge! You insufferable little *bitch*.‚Äù

She wipes her mouth. ‚ÄúYou‚Äôve had enough attention, anyway.‚Äù

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "Revenge for what, you violent lunatic!? You heroes always pick the dumbest things to get upset over! You're in poverty because of... this body's father's father? And not even directly!? Go blame your own lineage for abandoning you, you idiot! Or is it *really* because Alice liked me more? Are you just jealous of how cool I am!? Come back and fight me when you actually care about striking down evil!"

author.name: natyobb
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\ba6cc976522571d97f7cf7d74d5b3684-FF145.png

messages.content:
"I'm not in poverty because of you. That's not what this is about. But I'm the... the only one who ever took you seriously. Even a little. You ruined that, of course. You ruin everything. I wanted to believe you so bad, Jane. But all you ever do is let me down. Even this." She gestures with her hands. 
"What the fuck is this?! This excuse for a fight. I *hate* you. I think you're a joke, you're pathetic, you can never amount to anything and I'll go until the day I dieeeee you bitch at long last why won't you fuckinggguuhhh--" She spits out blood.
"So strike me down, now. It can only be you. You know, I..." She laughs, holding her head. "When everything fell apart in succession, I tried to fill the void with love. I was a whooooore, Jane. Could've had some real nasty comeback material if you bothered to learn that, haha...! But none of those men ever loved me, or I them. It neeeever worked. I never thought of any of them when they weren't shoved directly into my face, they didn't-- like how babies, they don't have object permanend...nence. That was me with everyone. But not youuu... even after all these years, none of it has faded. You're the only person who's important to me, Jane. And I want you dead more than anything."
She looks down, her hair covering her face. "Funny."

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "...Gweh...?" Voreverl drops her sword, not out of conscious thought, but because her hands automatically move to cover her own face. She can't confirm with a mirror, but she's pretty sure she feels herself blushing. "I'm... portant? I mean, of course I am! You can lie and... say you pity me, that I'm a joke, whatever! That's all just banter, isn't it!? My evil has consumed you! It's... you get it! You are my archnemesis, aren't you!? You recognize that killing me is more important than anything!"

author.name: natyobb
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\ba6cc976522571d97f7cf7d74d5b3684-FF145.png

messages.content:
Violetta looks back up quickly. She doesn't blush, maybe because her blood is occupied, but she's obviously incredibly caught off guard by this. "Y--archne-!? This isn't--you haven't consumed me! This is meaningless! It's not a victory, or a relationship, it's an ending, and that's the best you'll ever get. And I never--I never said I pitied... well, that was... back when we were, were..."
She grits her teeth. "Why can't you make anything easy?!"

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "Gweheheh..." Voreverl removes her hands for the sake of a full shrug "How could you have expected a duel with Voreverl Leocot, the bringer of darkness and all that is unholy, the baroness of the kingdom of evil, the embodiment of the plague of despair, to be easy!? You just sound like a glutton for punishment to me. You think one of us dying will end this... but our battle will be told for eons to come! It will become the foundation of all future legends passed down throughout mankind! You said it yourself! Nothing is more important than me and you, right here, right now!"

author.name: natyobb
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\ba6cc976522571d97f7cf7d74d5b3684-FF145.png

messages.content: Violetta grabs your shoulders and shoves you against the rooftop door, taking advantage of your unarmed status. ‚ÄúHow do you do it?! How do you so devotedly keep up the act of all this shit you must know is fucking nonsense?‚Äù

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "...How do *you* do it? How do you live your ordinary, simple, meaningless life? I can't pretend to be like you! Like anyone else! Like some caged animal, indistinguishable from any other lab rat running for the sake of some... incomprehensible societal goal! I don't care about the economy, about staying out of poverty, about your stupid petty little romances and families! How do you *not* want to be like me!? Like *Voreverl Leocot*!?"

author.name: natyobb
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\ba6cc976522571d97f7cf7d74d5b3684-FF145.png

messages.content: ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs not a choice! It‚Äôs the truth. I *know* the truth. I‚Äôve *seen* beyond the fucking veil, and it confirmed what I already knew. Dust in the wind!  All that we do is pointless. I can‚Äôt delude myself into believing there‚Äôs some grand meaning, or some ‚Äòcool‚Äô edgy aesthetic, to the things I want, the people I‚Äôve hurt‚Ä¶ oh, but you can. ‚ÄúNot this time, Jane.‚Äù She‚Äôs an incredibly strong woman. The physical resistance isn‚Äôt enough. Her grip around your throat tightens and makes it difficult to speak. ‚ÄúHa. You‚Äôre begging. P‚Ä¶pathetic. I can‚Äôt believe you‚Ä¶‚Äù
She places the whole weight of her body against you. She falls forward, in other words. Her hands trail off you as her head limply makes contact with your torso, with the rest of her body stumbling to the ground. Violetta lays there, unconscious.

author.name: onnieee

messages.content: Fear. It's fear, isn't it? But that's... patently ridiculous. It's just a *body*. Me puppeting it doesn't give this body any kind of greater symbolic or spiritual *meaning.* It's just meat and circuitry and neurons firing all indiscriminate. If my mental understanding of myself doesn't align with what I end up seeing in the mirror, then.. why would that matter? Why do I even have a mental understanding of myself at *all*? It's entirely irrelevant to my goals. There's nothing to be afraid of, you pathetic coward. Whatever stupid, stupid physiological response you had the last time you looked at your reflection, back on Earth - you can overcome that, easily. I tell myself all of this sternly.

author.name: onnieee
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\af114b26c161ebe1376c2e8061cbd7d4-EDAEE.png

messages.content: Me. I stare at the me in the mirror. The person there is me. It's my body, and I... I'm fine with it. I can logically and clinically identify it as myself. There's no - biological response, or anything. Maybe my pulse speeds up a bit. A bit. But it's.. none of this is relevant. It's still me, no matter the fear, no matter the immediate disconnect, no matter....

author.name: onnieee
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\af114b26c161ebe1376c2e8061cbd7d4-EDAEE.png

messages.content: Hah. Haah. I don't even know... what to call myself, do I? I put.. so much stock in the idea of giving myself a different name, as if that would be at all *helpful*. But I can't... I can't go by any of the previous names anymore. There's - there's baggage attached to the name I *used* to go by, political and social consequences of continuing to identify myself as such... and it wasn't my real name, to begin with. I don't have a real name. It's been this sequence of aliases for as long as I can remember.

messages.content: I laugh, my voice scratchy. This has all started to feel.. tremendously irrelevant. Just a few hours ago, I was.. what? Planning to reinvent myself on Earth, an entirely different person? Distinct from all of this fabricated, truly made-up bullshit? The youngest, most irrelevant member of the royal family staging a coup and psychically influencing everyone in the near vicinity to resonate with her on some lower psychological level is the peak of internal corruption, the paternalistic monarchist garbage that I'm supposed to be so staunchly against, in theory. But all it's done is make Arctica feel even less real than before. Avdol's a lunatic. I realized that after less than a minute of speaking to him. And I had been.. so invested in proving him wrong, in proving that Artica's "created-ness" was a fabrication.. or, if it was true, that it had meaningful consequences for the people living there, with their complex internal lives.. but I'm living here. I don't have any of that. I'm only nominally real. If Arctica is fake, that means I'm fake too.

"I've been going by that name for a long time. So I understand if it's difficult for you to get used to a new one. But.." I spread my arms, lying extravagantly for the imaginary camera. "It'll still be me. No matter what I'm called." 

I don't believe this, because I never could. To reassure Bern that I'm the same person is reliant on... some continuity of self that I fundamentally lack. But Bern knows who he is. I can't burden him with the knowledge that he's been saddled with a pale reflection of something real. Because it's so easy for Bern, isn't it? Tossed recklessly between bodies but still retaining this fundamental grasp of his *soul* or whatever the fuck. Just going along with the fucking flow, right? He's got it aaaaaaalllll figured out.

Theseus pushes the resentment down. The fact of the matter is, that's not a particularly useful feeling to be having right now. So they throw it away. They stop referring to themselves in the first person, for the time being - it's so much *easier* to not have to pretend that there's a "me" to speak of, something other than the most bare-bones collection of embarrassing impulses. This is *so* much better.

"I'm going by Theseus right now. But it's still me." They lie.

messages.content: "Power." Solnit addresses Gratia with the end of some exchange before turning back to Viotto. "I can't say for sure how long any of us have, but it feels like denying *any* need to rush would be inaccurate."

messages.content: "I have many irons in the fire, many processes involved in. I am currently attempting to delegate one of them to someone else, because a lot of things are currently ongoing. In terms of physical destination, I only hope to find a more central location from which it is easier to orient ourselves." Solnit manages to avoid any concrete information.

‚ÄúIntuition, call it. It‚Äôs better than staying still. As warped as things have become, getting somewhere does still require going somewhere. That‚Äôs a rule that was preserved.‚Äù

He starts walking ahead, picking at seemingly random when a crossroads is reached. ‚ÄúI would not consider you someone well versed in the concept of power, Mr. Entenmann.‚Äù

‚ÄúUgh.‚Äù Gratia rolls her eyes and follows him.

messages.content: I follow along the branching paths. "Oh? You wouldn't? and yet... our very first interaction was that of me changing your very career trajectory, upsetting Dextrum's opinion of your academic virtues. You will never occupy the position of those lost behind you again, Sol... and that is because of me. I would not demean Entenmann so lightly."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "And I'm glad you're not too far gone to be beyond self-reflection."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
‚ÄúToo far gone. Tch. I never thought I was a good fit for that kind of instructive role. I merely have to listen to that man for the time being.‚Äù

‚ÄúYou seem like a bad fit for any role that involves interacting with anyone, honestly.‚Äù Gratia.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "I don't think that's true, Gratia. For somebody to not be a fit for any type of interaction would render them a non-existence in this world. Even if he cannot be the instructor, he has many options left to him."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "Even he agrees that he must become a listener. Right?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
‚ÄúNot in whatever way you‚Äôre likely implying.‚Äù He stops beside a door.

‚ÄúThere‚Äôs a lot to life beyond being social. Obviously I‚Äôm good at all of it, but y‚Äôknow. Not like he wouldn‚Äôt exist just because he‚Äôs a loser.‚Äù Gratia.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
‚ÄúHow could ceasing to exist being the least of someone‚Äôs problems? That‚Äôs literally the biggest a problem could be.‚Äù Gratia rolls her eyes.

Solnit peers through the doorway. ‚ÄúThere‚Äôs potentially fates worth than death, I suppose‚Ä¶‚Äù He speaks quietly.

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "Even if there were no such thing as a fate worse than death, that wouldn't negate what I'm saying. If you had to kill two people to stay alive yourself, for example, do you suppose that would be a relatively small issue?"

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

‚ÄúWhy would I care if I had to kill people to save my own life? It‚Äôs literally not even a moral issue at that point.‚Äù Gratia scoffs. She then stares at Solnit, curiously.

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "What's your upper limit? Would you commit genocide to sustain yourself? Omnicide?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "Not a moral issue, you say..."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "I'm a simple man, Gratia. I believe in the sanctity of life, above all else. I merely view life as a function of social communication, rather than a specific biological state. You seem... a little behind even the basic premise, to be honest."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: I turn to Sol. "What others? What golem?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
‚ÄúI‚Äôm ahead of the game. You‚Äôve obviously never had to make a choice like that, old man.‚Äù

‚ÄúShut up, both of you.‚Äù Solnit mutters. He pulls out an oblong object wrapped in cloth and shoves it into Gratia‚Äôs hands. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs all yours if you pull this off.‚Äù

‚ÄúYeah, sure. I‚Äôm in the middle of owning this guy, though.‚Äù She turns back to Viotto. ‚ÄúI mean, I could do the same ridiculous extrapolation. Would you let yourself die to save a horse? A fly? At some point that has to be unsustainable.‚Äù

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
"That's specifically why in my hypothetical, it was two people. It's true that there are some grey areas in the middle of the scale - say, sacrificing yourself for somebody younger than you, or one who's more likely to make a difference in the areas that you care about. But if you don't wish to die, it's a basic moral fact that you must also try to create a world where others don't impose unnecessary death upon anyone else, or even themselves."
"No, I would not sacrifice myself for a fly. Because a fly is below me. They feed into the social cycle so, so much less. And so the only way you could justify mass murder is if you believed yourself more important than everyone else. Do you? Do you find life inherently worthless? I don't see why you're doing anything here, in that case. Simply curl up in a ball on the floor and fill your veins with your medicine of choice. I won't look down on you for that."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
Solnit walks away down a different hallway. "I will see you both later. There is something else I need to attend to."

"I'm not going to kill myself because I think my life is valuable. That makes absolutely no sense. Are you senile?" She chuckles. "I'm inherently different from everyone else. Because I'm me. If other people die, that doesn't change my existence. But if I do, that changes everything."

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "It's often given to people in their last moments, but that's not a requirement. It can be sustained however long you want."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "Might've heard something similar. That's not sustainable, though. I'm not the type of person who can afford even simpler pleasures. That's what this is all about." She walks through the door.

‚ÄúI guess I never thought about my relationships with other people that way - in terms of ‚Äúfate‚Äù or ‚Äúpredestination‚Äù, which, quite frankly, I don‚Äôt think really exist. But no, I wouldn‚Äôt associate with someone going out of their way to hurt me.‚Äù

messages.content: "Ah, but that's exactly the issue - you believe that being hurt requires the other person to go our of their way to attempt at it. No, interpersonal pain comes in many forms, Rowan, not the least of which is accidental, or, more importantly, due to simple incompatibility. If you search long enough, you will find this compatibility I speak of... that is what I talk about, not quite fate, but a process of natural selection. For some people, indeed, it is worth fighting fate for. But most are meant to be tested and moved past. That is the progression of life we all know, chancing at a relationship. So I ask; are these people who naturally interlocked with your self-conception, or are they forcing themselves into it for a shared goal? I would be wary of the latter, son."

messages.content: ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt know. I doubt I have any insight you don‚Äôt.‚Äù She jolts slightly at Viotto‚Äôs voice, but doesn‚Äôt turn to him.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "What were you hoping to accomplish here, then?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: I shuffle my feet around a bit, nervous for some reason. The atmosphere here is unsettling...

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "Nothing. There's nothing at all I can accomplish here. Don't you get it?"

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "Yes, I think I understand. You feel defeated, of course... as many would in this situation. A strange place we're in, a lack of meaningful direction. But we must try, you know? Maybe it sounds like a bit of a generic motivational statement, but... in the end, the fact that I don't get it, as you say, is a factor in my favor."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: I point towards a building. "Why not check in there?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: She turns to Viotto and her eyes narrow briefly. "You're still a man of faith, if I remember your words. Do you believe that hell exists?" This is a weird thing to say.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "Yes, I do. Although, I'm of the doctrine that there are no unforgivable sins. Hell is a place meant to convince the prideful to finally repent, after a life of being denied that right. It's not permanent unless one chooses it to be so. Does that help with your question?" Whatever it is.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: ‚ÄúThat‚Äôs a bizarrely liberal view.‚Äù She looks at you slightly differently. ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt agree. If it‚Äôs real, I think it‚Äôs what lies past the point of persuasion. A place to maximize suffering. And I think that includes‚Ä¶ all kinds.‚Äù

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "That seems reductive. It includes all kinds of suffering, yes, because it is the *ultimate* suffering. Everyone likely agrees on that. But that means that we can't really conceptualize what that would be like by relating it to any of our current feelings of distress. It's much like comparing ourselves to bugs - technically feasible, and, indeed, morally correct, but only useful to a very specific degree. I would be wary of what 'kinds' you wish to speak of here."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "After all, you seem to believe in something past the point of persuasion... a worrying ethic in practice."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: ‚ÄúIt doesn‚Äôt matter what I believe. The world is what it is regardless. I‚Äôm just saying that there‚Äôs some comfort in that idea, right? Or there would be. It‚Äôs why I guess I can understand that view of yours. Because if a sinner is past the point of no return, even as their organs are boiled and their minds tormented, some part of them can rest easy knowing there‚Äôs nothing to be done about it.‚Äù

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "Why do you think the demons of Hell would have to resort to boiling somebody's organs? What I said about being unable to conceptualize it - that extends beyond emotional issues, and into physical means of suffering as well. God and his enemies are the very basis of the supernatural as we imagine it, after all. It's easy to invent flowery language to visualize the 'ultimate suffering', as I put it, but these are merely aids, not the truth of the matter. Their souls exist, and they are in infinite agony. There is no other action or state we need to invoke."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: ‚ÄúMy point was going to be that I don‚Äôt think people in hell get to understand that that‚Äôs where they are.‚Äù She shrugs. ‚ÄúBut frankly, your description feels absurd in line with before. Who‚Äôs gonna be motivated to change by a state of infinite agony?‚Äù

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "Who isn't?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "I don't see your point, anyways. I assume you're saying that this city is Hell? Magnolia, dear, if you're right about the fact that people in Hell aren't allowed the understanding of their existence in it, how could you possibly think that you've worked it out? The moment you came to the conclusion, it would be disproven. You don't get to circumvent the rules of your own logic merely because you're struggling."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "Please, just let me know if there's anything I can do to alleviate it."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: ‚ÄúA catch-22, yeah. I thought of that. Not sure how to resolve it.  But anyway‚Ä¶ No one would be motivated to change by senseless and aimless torment. In the real world, torture just gets people to blurt out any confession or statement they think will make it stop for even the briefest of moments. It‚Äôd be like that. They‚Äôd try to think of how to make it seem like they‚Äôd changed. If hell served the purpose you‚Äôre talking about, I‚Äôd imagine something closer to like‚Ä¶ Dante‚Äôs Inferno. The dumb ironic punishments for different varieties of sinner.‚Äù

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "What makes you believe you would be capable of lying in Hell?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: ‚ÄúIf God was willing to prevent that, why would hell even exist? The entire reason he allows suffering is supposed to be for the sake of free will. If he puts them on a track where they can do nothing *but* redeem themselves, what was the point of any of it?‚Äù

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "They are not forced to redeem themselves. They can continue suffering. A lack of redemption leads to suffering here as well. Do you think that violates free will?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "What do you think free will is, if not allowing us the choice to continue suffering? Perhaps you've gotten cause and effect mixed up."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: ‚ÄúWhy would they be prevented from lying? What would be the point of that? It wouldn‚Äôt be a conscious lie, anyway. People can believe they‚Äôre good and be wrong.‚Äù She looks back up at the sky. ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt, anyway, so that‚Äôs irrelevant. I don‚Äôt need to lie to be like this.‚Äù

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "Why do you think somebody would be able to get out of Hell simply by claiming that they're good? Is that what repentance is to you? Self-aggrandization? I wouldn't think..."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "...be like what?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: I squint at her.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
‚ÄúI don‚Äôt. I‚Äôm saying the exact opposite. That they wouldn‚Äôt be able to escape because that‚Äôs all they‚Äôd ever try to do, and obviously that wouldn‚Äôt result in anything. That‚Äôs the *entire* crux of my argument, of this whole line of questioning. God, what the hell‚Äî what is this? Have you ever actually *listened* to someone else in your entire life? Or do you just pick up enough keywords to form whatever sentence you want to be able to hear yourself talk with, like some child phoning in their book report.‚Äù

She pauses long enough for Viotto to maybe start saying something, and then keeps talking anyway. ‚ÄúWhich is fine.
I‚Äôm in no place to judge. I‚Äôm the exact same. Not once, a single time, have I ever put in enough effort to understand anything about you. I didn‚Äôt understand my daughter either. I don‚Äôt think I really knew my husband past a surface level. I don‚Äôt get to know other people. But I know one thing about you now.‚Äù

She looks back at you and smiles slightly. ‚ÄúI went through the most aimless torment imaginable. With some help from my parents. It never made me stronger, or a better person. It made me paranoid. It made me stubborn. It made me condescending, and clueless, and alone. It made me constantly speak over anyone I thought I was above or knew better than. It made me like *you*.‚Äù
She laughs. ‚ÄúIt really took me so long to realize.‚Äù

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
"Well, I'm glad I could be of some help during your torment, at least."
He smiles.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
‚ÄúWe really do fucking deserve each other.‚Äù

The ground shakes slightly. The sky shifts. It looks, for a moment, as if all of existence is under the floorboards of some building. Then it returns to what it looked like prior.

‚ÄúI don‚Äôt even care anymore. Things are just going to keep happening randomly until I die. Haha!‚Äù

((End chapter))

messages.content:
I'm not going to bother with the pretense of her agency here. It's a fucking cutscene from the perspective of a regular human's capabilities. It all happens too unreasonably fast.

The first thing that happens as Erica Furuda begins to move through the door after Eulogia Praxis and Virtos Dextrum is that the ground shakes. 

Secondly, she'd hear Virtos and Eulogia gasp in surprise at something occurring in the room ahead.

Third, above the doorway, a thick, thorn-covered vine bursts through the wall and continues its slithering over against the ceiling of the room, incredibly quickly. 

Fourth, two more elsewhere do the same. The room becomes engulfed in this twisted plant life too rapidly for it to be worthwhile to enumerate all of them.

Fifth. Two more people enter this crossroads of a room from the left and right respectively, meeting one another's eyes. Erica doesn't recognize the one on the left. On the right is Nerissa, who Erica might barely remember.

And lastly... the room begins to collapse. Nerissa is blocked off by a falling fragment of the roof. Rene screams and runs forward, shoving Erica to the ground. She loses consciousness.

Erica finishes the chapter.

messages.content: "Haha, yeah." Catarina ignores most of this response. "The triangle is to make it easier to get the balls in their starting position. They're all bunched together, and your goal is to get them into holes in the right order, or the right ones, depending on what specific game you're playing. You strike this clustered mass in what's called a *break*. You don't know where the balls are gonna end up; it's too chaotic to say for certain. But you need things to be separated and altered somehow so you can work from there." She nods to herself. "You get it now?"

messages.content: "No, that's why we'll do it."

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "You know, uh. The concept of freedom is such a wonderful thing to grasp, you know? But.... it's not something to actually be grasped. That's why religion works, you know? The concept of god is JUST right there at our shoulders, but not actually something we can... touch or feel! It may not even be real.... to some people."

author.name: theotherschilalyi
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\7ce08f8bae2d1252a0092c317eb39b0d-F721D.png

attachments.url: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\thoughtful-F72BC.png

messages.content: "I...... I was free once. I never really knew who my parents were as people. I may never know. My childhood was raised in mind for me to be my own person. I was the one who read my own books and gained my own education, occasionally asking my dad and mom for things where they would give a. Three to four word response?"

author.name: theotherschilalyi
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\7ce08f8bae2d1252a0092c317eb39b0d-F721D.png

messages.content: "In concept, I was forced to learn business, but that wasn't really true. There exactly wasn't a big push to do so. And that's why I'm here, you know? How I became a criminal, met some shady people, went to Japan, got uh. arrested. Tried to get myself a partner on earth and now I'm facing charges for sexual harassment. Murdered some politican back in Arctica? Jeez, it's been so long."

author.name: theotherschilalyi
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\7ce08f8bae2d1252a0092c317eb39b0d-F721D.png

messages.content: "None of those weren't good. None of them weren't good at all! Those are capital crimes, damnit. And they aren't capital crimes that mean anything! Who- I have no idea the name of the person I murdered. I did it... just because!"

author.name: theotherschilalyi
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\7ce08f8bae2d1252a0092c317eb39b0d-F721D.png

attachments.url: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\afraid-575F3.png

messages.content: "Yeah, I can wander around whatever the name of the mafia I'm in. But I sure don't know what the hell I'm supposed to do! What do they remotely need me for in the first place! And this is precisely because I was free. I was never part of the whatever family they run. I just... I just exist."

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\7ce08f8bae2d1252a0092c317eb39b0d-F721D.png

‚ÄúHey, no one NEEDS to have everything figured out, you know.‚Äù Catarina puts a hand on your shoulder.

‚ÄúSorry, facing what charges? Huh?‚Äù Skelt.

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "Yes, Skelt. Sexual harassment. So you know that Horatius Kyodu person? Yeah. It's just the fucking end for me now when I inevitably transfer back to Tunisia."

author.name: theotherschilalyi
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\7ce08f8bae2d1252a0092c317eb39b0d-F721D.png

messages.content: "Really? *Horatius*? Hoh." Catarina makes a strange face. "I mean out of all people... well, what did you do? Did you learn anything?" She asks, much more lighthearted than the situation possibly demands.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "I confessed my love to them and I... well tried to kiss them before I got tackled."

author.name: theotherschilalyi
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\7ce08f8bae2d1252a0092c317eb39b0d-F721D.png

messages.content: "Oh. That's literally nothing." Catarina shrugs. "I doubt that's illegal anywhere."

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "Yes... because I was tackled before I could go forward with it."

author.name: theotherschilalyi
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\7ce08f8bae2d1252a0092c317eb39b0d-F721D.png

messages.content:
"Yeah, but the ends are what matter, not the means, right?" Catarina gestures as though this is obvious and sensible.

Wress Hifele, who is this man, ducks from a nearby scuffle into the hallway Catarina and Intuition are currently conversing in to catch his breath.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
Catarina continues speaking. "Even if you did, that's not a crime. It's just obnoxious. Oh, hi Wress."

Wress is silent.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "Yeah. Yeah fuck. Yeah of course you come in when I'm talking about Horatius."

author.name: theotherschilalyi
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\7ce08f8bae2d1252a0092c317eb39b0d-F721D.png

author.name: theotherschilalyi
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\7ce08f8bae2d1252a0092c317eb39b0d-F721D.png

messages.content: "You know, it's kind of funny, I.. I don't think I've seen you like. Alive."

author.name: theotherschilalyi
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\7ce08f8bae2d1252a0092c317eb39b0d-F721D.png

messages.content:
"I don't..." Wress stares at Catarina, and then winces. He opts to look at Intuition instead. "My deal with them was nothing. We were colleagues part of the same political group. Anything else is unsubstantiated slander."

"Wress..." Catarina's voice takes on a more genuine tone than her perpetually flippant jokey attitude.

"You don't get to have an opinion on the problem you caused, Cat."

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "Did we meet together before? I remember seeing your body carried away unconscious."

author.name: theotherschilalyi
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\7ce08f8bae2d1252a0092c317eb39b0d-F721D.png

messages.content:
"I've never actually met you, no. I can assume that..."

"This is Intuition Overdrive." Catarina introduces you. "Intuition's kind of like you."

"Is he." Wress grimaces.

"Well, from my point of view. Whatever." Another incomprehensible Catarina statement. What a girlboss.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "Aaaanyways. Uh. Where was I on about? Oh yeah."

author.name: theotherschilalyi
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\7ce08f8bae2d1252a0092c317eb39b0d-F721D.png

messages.content:
"What? I have a plan. I have a lot of plans. This is all very thought out, this is the culmination of years and years of work. Cat, what kind of an impression are you giving?" Wress asks.

Catarina does the 'uh eto bleh' head thing. "So, there's three, and the first one is a collectivist commune. That's Wress's thing."

Wress shakes his head. "That's not really the way I'd put it."

"It's an ideal world he talks about, but impractical for larger scale societies."

"My proposed system, which is not the thing you said, is perfectly scalable if you account for proper redistricting along cultural boundaries, boundaries I have drawn up, and *shown* you the drawings, so I don't know why you're--"

"Don't bore everyone with the details, Wressy." Catarina turns to Skelt. "Edit this to make me look better."

"It's live." Skelt mutters.

"Whatever. The truth is more than enough." She flips her hair dramatically. "You're a good man, Wress. But you don't have the fire in your heart to be the leader of a nation."

Wress just stares at her silently.

messages.content: "What's a collective commune?"

author.name: theotherschilalyi

messages.content:
"An intentional community is a voluntary residential community which is designed to have a high degree of social cohesion and teamwork. The members of an intentional community typically hold a common social, political, religious, or spiritual vision, and typically share responsibilities and property. This way of life is sometimes characterized as an 'alternative lifestyle'. Intentional communities can be seen as social experiments or communal experiments." Catarina.

"What? Is that from an encyclopedia? Did you memorize that? Huh?" Wress stares at her less silently.

"Information is power. Also, I wanted to show you up at some point. Like now." She sticks out her tongue playfully.

"God, this is all just some game to you, isn't it?! I don't know why I thought you'd finally change when things got real." Wress fumes. "And there aren't only three systems of government! What kind of definition would you be using that believes that?!"

"Obviously there's nuance, yes." Catarina rolls her eyes.

This conversation is really important, and matters.

And even if this weren't the case, one man being wrong is not a good excuse to throw out an entire system."

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\96bfd6970100265a0c5139863721722f-0A978.png

messages.content:
‚ÄúIt isn‚Äôt only a gender thing. ‚Ä¶Though that does raise a question. Why are you here, your majesty?‚Äù
Thelma grins, addressing Zita again. ‚ÄúI mean, shouldn‚Äôt this kind of message go to your husband? What‚Äôs this confrontation of wives, eh? Ideally, my ex-husband would be the one doing this, haha. But he‚Äôs no longer with us. What about you?‚Äù

‚ÄúHe‚Äôs not enough of a fool to wander around openly while the building is compromised.‚Äù Zita stares her down.

‚ÄúAnd you are?‚Äù

‚ÄúI care not what you think of me.‚Äù She readies her weapon.

‚ÄúI wouldn‚Äôt do that if I were you. I‚Äôm not rambling blindly. I know a lot. I‚Äôm the receptionist, you know. I keep records.‚Äù

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: ‚Äú‚Ä¶Thelma, please, calm down. There is no need to jump to a confrontation here. You‚Äôre in front of the queen. You have all that you need. Talk things out with her, like an adult.‚Äù

author.name: thebeginnersguide
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\96bfd6970100265a0c5139863721722f-0A978.png

messages.content:
‚ÄúI‚Äôm perfectly calm. I‚Äôm not the one likely about to kill someone.‚Äù

‚ÄúAre you threatening me?‚Äù Zita grunts.

‚ÄúThat is the opposite of what I just said.‚Äù

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: ‚Äú‚Ä¶‚Äù

author.name: thebeginnersguide
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\96bfd6970100265a0c5139863721722f-0A978.png

messages.content:
"I don't have time for this. You've admitted to treason and your life is forfeit." Zita's expression tenses.

The other man who entered with Thelma runs to stand in between them. "Your majesty. She has not faced trial for her crimes."

"Is this a joke? Are you a fool?"

"I don't really get what you're doing either." Thelma.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "...Excuse me." Joliene contributes to the conversation by asking the man a question. "Who exactly are you?"

author.name: thebeginnersguide
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\96bfd6970100265a0c5139863721722f-0A978.png

messages.content:
"My name is Proso. I am of the Guard. I was not stationed here until recently. Well met, Ms. Swansong."

"You should consider yourself lucky I was desperate enough to make up for losses that I resorted to the likes of you." Zita scolds him.

"I am. I am thankful for this. Nonetheless, I am not going to allow the course of justice to be perverted by a poorly thought spur-of-the-moment decision."

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "Then if I may be so bold, I agree with you, Proso. I... have difficulty believing that what's happening here is as simple as an insurrection. I couldn't tell you what it actually is, if not that, but it would be hasty to kill anyone before we've understood the full situation."

author.name: thebeginnersguide
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\96bfd6970100265a0c5139863721722f-0A978.png

messages.content:
"I find insurrections quite complex, actually." Thelma says.

"..." Zita and Proso meet each other's eyes for a few moments. Zita relaxes her body slightly. "If nothing else, I suppose she can be useful for one of interrogation or a hostage."

"That is acceptable." Proso nods.

Thelma scoffs.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "Thank you. Thelma is an intelligent woman. I'm sure you'll find the interrogation to go quite smoothly." She smiles some.

author.name: thebeginnersguide
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\96bfd6970100265a0c5139863721722f-0A978.png

messages.content:
‚ÄúIs Receptionist like‚Ä¶ your real name?‚Äù Proso starts this ‚Äòinterrogation‚Äô.

‚ÄúWhat‚Äôs a real name, anyway? I‚Äôve found no one can meaningfully describe that.‚Äù She dodges the question.

No one really has a response to that.

‚Äú‚Ä¶But yes, legally. I managed to have it changed. You probably can‚Äôt find records of what it used to be. I didn‚Äôt even abuse my position for that, the record-keeping is just that poor.‚Äù Thelma bemoans the flaws within Arctican bureaucracy.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
Joliene blinks.

"Why? Why would you do that?"

author.name: thebeginnersguide
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\96bfd6970100265a0c5139863721722f-0A978.png

messages.content:
‚ÄúI was feeling really pretentious. At the time, I probably would‚Äôve given you some long explanation about the deceit of passivity, of the power in fading into a role. It was really stupid. Embarrassing in hindsight.‚Äù She holds her head, chuckling.
‚ÄúI also thought it was funny they allowed me to do it. I was at kind of a low point, willing to become a joke for convenience. As for changing it, uh, I guess the cat‚Äôs out of the bag, so I‚Äôll say it was to separate myself from my husband since I knew there‚Äôd be a chance he‚Äôd blow up as an enemy of the state and ruin my life by association. I was surprised Elithabeza maintained power with the Hifele name, actually. I guess it wasn‚Äôt necessary.‚Äù

We‚Äôre all mildly blown away by this stunning revelation.

‚ÄúOh, okay.‚Äù Proso.

‚ÄúWhat??‚Äù Zita.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: "...I'm not sure I get it?"

author.name: thebeginnersguide
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\96bfd6970100265a0c5139863721722f-0A978.png

messages.content:
"Even after all I've done to separate myself from him..." Thelma sighs. "I guess you can never really escape your past. My husband's name was Tebar Hifele. He was an awful man who happened to have politics I agreed with. He wasn't there for me, he wasn't there for our son when it counted, and he used the pretense of being an active political figure and covert criminal to live a double life with *some woman* without my knowledge. So I found out and I left him! And I *won*, alright?! What's about to happen wouldn't have been able to without me. I've done more through cunning than that idiot ever could."

Zita is gradually getting more pissed again. Proso doesn't care about this.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: Joliene seems to take a moment to decide how she feels about this.

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\96bfd6970100265a0c5139863721722f-0A978.png

messages.content:
Proso is still standing between Zita and Thelma.

"...I can't very well have my men distracted trying to fight *me*. We'll deal with her later." She turns and walks away from Thelma to the back wall of the room.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

"..."

"Okay."

She follows her after a moment.

author.name: thebeginnersguide
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\96bfd6970100265a0c5139863721722f-0A978.png

messages.content:
She‚Äôs not really going anywhere, but okay.

She presses an indent on the wall. Nothing happens. ‚ÄúFuck.‚Äù Zita says.

‚ÄúWhat is it?‚Äù Proso.

‚ÄúSomeone‚Äôs already messed with whatever security system you have here, presumably. I wasn‚Äôt involved with the specific military operations of invading.‚Äù Thelma.

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

"Is that so?"

author.name: thebeginnersguide
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\96bfd6970100265a0c5139863721722f-0A978.png

messages.content:
‚ÄúI can‚Äôt create a barrier around this room. It‚Äôs not working. How did‚Ä¶‚Äù

‚ÄúAny number of traitors. Virtos Dextrum? Arrive Sinestre? One of the Guard? Even I‚Äôm not sure how many exactly are involved in this.‚Äù Thelma exposits.

‚ÄúYou are lying! We have been betrayed, but not so overwhelmingly, and your hideous mindgames don‚Äôt stand a chance at‚Ä¶‚Äù Zita takes a deep breath. ‚ÄúProso, go and restrain her. *Elsewhere*. There should be rope or something nearby.‚Äù

Proso nods and goes off to do this.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:

‚ÄúI‚Äôve no choice but to trust in your principles, I suppose.‚Äù Zita rolls her eyes.

She squints in the direction of what lies beyond this room. ‚Äú‚Ä¶I think I might need to get involved.‚Äù

messages.content:
Wress is a weakling who is still injured, one arm slung in a cast. He's only this far into the fray for morale purposes. He's not alone, but there's a point where he's isolated enough. Where Wyrd can find an opportunity to shove the man escorting Wress aside and stab him with 'his' blade.

So Wyrd does that, inflicting a lethal wound to the chest. Amazing.

At the same time, Wress reacts instinctually to an approaching threat, albeit too slowly. He flails a serrated dagger pathetically, managing to snag it onto Wyrd's mask.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
This is, to be clear, the only reason I am bothering describing this encounter. The facsimile of a human face worn on top of a real face that Wyrd sports shatters into two pieces, one falling off 'his' face. It then becomes apparent to anyone with eyes that Wyrd is Zita Praxis.

Wow. Really? Her. Zita? The queen of Arctica? She was Wyrd the whole time. No way. It was her. This fact, which should have been fucking *obvious* to anyone who holds any amount of reasonable knowledge about either of the two, let alone the half of the relevant cast who were basically told it directly, is unambiguously universal info. Fuck you, Zita. You don't get to be Batman. You're a senile old woman and we're going to interact with you on those terms.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
At the moment their eyes meet, Wress smiles slightly. Because he knows, ultimately, he's won. There is no realistic way the monarchy wins this battle. They are surrounded, and all odds are against them. He believes fully he is going to die very soon, but that his ideals will survive and thrive. So he's happy. Like an idiot.

At the moment their eyes meet, Zita's expression darkens, frowning slightly with a hopeless gaze in her eyes. It's not because she's realized this fact about the tactical impossibility of her victory. It's not even because of her identity being outed to the world, though that's certainly uncomfortable to her. No, it's because she feels *bad*. Because she internalizes she's murdering another stunted mentally ill child, someone she can't dehumanize as without the all important concept of Family since she's personally met his. So she feels regret for the thing she's currently still actively doing. She feels sad. Like an idiot.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
What a joke. My narration is pretty lousy right now because I can't take any of this as serious or worth any decorum. Sorry!

Wyrd withdraws her blade, still partially in shock. Wress is hastily rushed away by his lieutenant with futile urgency, leaving the fight to others who will easily pick up the slack and in doing so prove that it was obviously idiotic for Wress to be situated where he was. The end. You'll have a whole chapter for Zita to circlejerk about how complex and tortured she is, don't worry.

‚ÄúI do not take orders from you.‚Äù Rene says this to PH, who she was earlier in the process of taking orders from.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
"Well, ...Rene," PH stumbles over her name. "you're obviously here for a reason, and I can't very well int--"

"My iteration in Arctica! The connection has been severed. Entirely." Rene frowns.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
"Your iteration..." PH stares confused for a moment. "Oh. Hm. Why were you even there?"

"Do you keep track of what happens in your project that little?!" Rene yells.

"I stay up to date on what's important."

"No you don't."

"I do. I can't be bothered to track some asinine technicality about unimportant non-participant parties. Do you expect me to remember Richard Ogden?" PH gestures to the air to indicate the absurdity of such a thing. "I do, but only because I was directly involved."

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
"You've only been involved in one meaningful thing in your entire miserable life." Rene closes the distance between the two of them. "And you spent years not remaining up to date. And here you are doing it again."

PH is uncomfortable with this amount of closeness, and gets out of his seat. "I don't..."

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
"I am not interested in excuses."

"Okay, then what *are* you interested in?" PH snaps. "Why are you even here? Are you that clingy to someone you claim disinterest in, that you show up to inform me of every trifling detail?"

Rene blinks. "Um. I. I mean. I thought it was important you know, since you nominally have some responsibility. And I demand you send me back."

"Back? You don't even know that anything happened there. In fact, you have no idea *when* it happened. Maybe you're confusing some signal from way in the distant future."

"We both know that is not how it works." Rene glares. "I am dead, or close to it. Erica will likely be mildly upset by this, which is unacceptable."

"...I will never understand what went wrong with you."

"No, you wouldn't." She smiles. "I'm not asking. This is an order. We both know I'm capable of outmatching you in a physical altercation."

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
"Well, I can't. It doesn't work that way." PH scowls. "Do you think I'm an idiot? That I wouldn't have tried testing that? If you're out of the picture in Arctica, that's your own problem to reap the consequences of."

Rene stares. She does a lot of staring. She grabs PH by the neck. "Is that so? You sure you want to stick to that?"

"Ngh." He sweats. "...Yes. It's the truth, and I'm sure you have the sense to understand that." He isn't sure of this in the slightest.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
"..." Rene lets him go. "Very well."

"Are you going to actually do what I asked?" PH mutters, recovering quickly from a brush with murderous intent.

"Perhaps. I also want The Antarctica Project to... properly conclude." Rene turns to exit.

"Ominous. But I'm already aware you hope Big Man breaks all my bones or somesuch."

"Ha ha." Rene chuckles. It's an artificial sounding laugh.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
But she is earnestly amused. Happy. Excited, even. This is a roadblock. But it doesn't change that the event she is preparing for will be incredible. Not for the reasons PH thinks, obviously. It will right the wrongs of the world, finally set in motion a more proper order of things. No more secrets. No more hiding. No more fear. It will be the greatest moment, she thinks, of her entire excuse for a life.

Because it will be the worst moment of his.

messages.content:
Bern steps back. He earnestly wasn't expecting that extreme or lengthy of a response, it seems. "No, I..." His expression betrays some regret. But it loses its softness as he continues. "I would never think you'd pull back any curtain to reveal some kind of hidden truth to me. That's not like you. I'm not accusing you of that. Or of trying to hurt me. I don't even know if you ever were anything but completely straightforward when describing how you felt about me. Words like love are complicated."
He looks down at Furn. He is progressively doing a worse and worse job at keeping his composure. "I don't think I'm a joke to you because you're not real. You think I'm a joke because *I'm* not real."
He looks towards Gratia cautiously. Then back to you. "And while we're being honest, here's my confession: I knew. I knew and I led you on. I let you do it because it made me feel better about myself."
Bern's eyes dilate slightly, looking towards nothing in particular. "I mean, it's a nice idea, isn't it? That none of *my* problems are real. I wanted to believe it too. That I was fine. This isn't about me, is it? It's about *you*. I'm just here to help you out, provide moral support. When we reunite, you can talk all about this mysterious stressful project you've gotten wrapped up in." 
Bern grabs his shoulders, shivering briefly. Or, he grabs one shoulder with one hand, and attempts to do the other before realizing he's still awkwardly holding a sword with that one. "We don't need to talk about me. We don't need to talk about how *months* went by. About having no one. That's just some background info. Oh, and being forced into a woman's body all that time? Nope, I wouldn't have any feelings about that. Just something quirky that happens to me! I'm not *complicated*! It's me, Bernard Zie, your friend! Your lover. I would've mentioned something messy like that. I would've made talking about it my whole identity."

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content: Theseus takes a step forward, feeling - marooned. Angry. Lost. "What...?" They choke out, unmoored. "No, Bern, that's not true, you're not... you're allowed to be complicated." Their face twists in an expression of pain. "Especially with regards to getting kidnapped and shoved into a body that's not yours!" Their breathing is heavy. "I can help! I wanted to help, from the beginning! I don't know why you think of yourself this way, but I never thought. I never thought you were fake. I thought *I* was fake. But being around you made me feel..."

They're so small, clasped between Theseus's own, so small and soft that for a moment Theseus can pretend that Theseus isn't the fucking woman in this equation. Theseus says, agonized - "You didn't lead me on! You didn't. You care about me, I know you do, you have to." Their chin is trembling. "We can talk, we can talk, about *whatever* you want, about all your fucking problems - just don't -"

Bern's upset over being trapped in a woman's body for what, two months? How about his *entire fucking life?* Does he think this is anything other than something to fucking *work through in silence??* Complicated? Messy? Lonely? Even abandoned completely in an alien world Bern still managed to find companions *instantly*, because he's just so loveable, he's so good. He's doing everything right. He's doing gender right. He's doing pain right. God, why can't Theseus get it? Why can't Theseus figure it out? What are they missing that Bern has that makes him worthy of kindness and love and affection, how do they get it *back*, h-how do they -

messages.content:
Bern's weapon clatters to the ground.
"What are you even asking for? What do you expect from me? I--" His expression seems bizarrely elated for a second before course-correcting. "I don't think I can ever give it to you. You're-- you're doing it now, you're describing me having *problems* as some farce, something I feel entitled to. And again, I-- I appreciate it. Furn, he always... everything was such a huge deal. He thought he was a psychologist. He thought every little thing I did was secretly about how much trauma I had. It was ridiculous. Like a buncha metal knows anything about that! Haha." He can't bring himself to force your hands away quite yet, so he resorts to kicking Furn's body with his foot. It hurts him. It's easy to tell that it hurts him. He does it hard enough to break his fucking bones, or at least tries. And that gives him the most genuine looking smile he's had this whole conversation. He shakes his head.

messages.content:
"Don't go...? Stop me, then. People love you. They loved Horatius, at least. They probably still love you. Our leader's obsessed with you. Furn constantly explains to me how clever you are. We meet a mysterious masked assailant, oh man-- I wonder who they allude to having some specific interest in!" He moves one hand out of your grip to gesture. "I get transported to a new world, I learn -- from the people biding their time until I get out of the way -- that I'm a *side-effect*, that I'm a consequence of the existence of the *real* people who matter. And I don't even need to check who among the people I know is one of those. People care about you so much it's a fucking problem -- and yes, I'm sorry about that! You've been put through a lot of shit for no good reason. But you're here. We're here. We made it. Not everyone did."
He sort of rushes through all of that. Bernard Zie catches his breath.

"If you love me... if you're such a master manipulator, the phantom who outran the law, if you can be anyone, if people keep obsessing over you... then fix me. Make me stop caring about this world, if it's so fake. Make me want only you. Can you? I'm an idiot, okay? It should be easier than anyone else." He says this like it's a joke, or an insult. But his eyes are still pleading.

messages.content: "Aagh..." Theseus says, wounded. Their heart is beating so fast. They feel like they've been set on fire, their entire body shaking. People don't.. people don't care about Theseus. They - they know that. They know that it's all constructed, that it's all a farce, a simulacrum of something real, because that's what they've always been. But Bern doesn't know that. Bern doesn't have to ever know that.

author.name: onnieee
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\af114b26c161ebe1376c2e8061cbd7d4-EDAEE.png

messages.content: Once, when Theseus was young and stupid and still on the run without any semblance of a support system, they had made the mistake of stealing a cigarette and three clementine slices from your standard Imperviat vendor. It hadn't been a mistake because they were caught or punished or taught anything about how thievery was bad or whatever. It had been a mistake because afterwards, they‚Äôd scaled the drainpipes to rest on the roof of an old townhouse, eating their hard-earned prize and thinking furiously about who's fault it was that Theseus was alone, who needed to suffer and pay for it. They coughed all the way through the cigarette and thought bitterly about all the things that had been taken from them, what little truth was gone. Watched the smoke curl up into smothered puffs, disappearing into the air. That was the principle of vapor; a thing that couldn't go back to the shape it once was. Theseus had shaken out their putty-shaped lungs and left them out to dry. Later that night, it began to rain.

author.name: onnieee
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\af114b26c161ebe1376c2e8061cbd7d4-EDAEE.png

messages.content: It was a mistake because Theseus could not be that child anymore. There were no more townhouses to climb. They had all been burned down.

messages.content: Theseus leans forward and kisses Bern on the mouth, cupping his face in a motion without tenderness, only conveying the urgency of the situation. He won't leave. He won't disappear. He can't. Theseus won't let it happen. I won't let it happen.

author.name: onnieee

messages.content:
Bern is caught off guard, but accepts the gesture and places a hand on your back. Good job, Theseus Rowe. You're successfully all he has left.

He withdraws from it. "I..." His head jerks abruptly to the side and he scampers to pick up the blade again.

Gratia is coming to. Or perhaps she already did, and is only getting up now. Maybe she was always conscious. "Sorry to interrupt this tender moment." Her speech is slightly slurred from her injury.

messages.content: Theseus turns around, scowling. They're trying very hard not to think about the implications of anything that just happened. "Do you feel like telling the truth, now?" They ask coldly.

Bern lifts his weapon.

‚ÄúBut I didn‚Äôt know it would kill him!‚Äù

‚ÄúShut up. That was too specific of a method.‚Äù Bern lifts up the blade.

‚ÄúNot buying that, huh?‚Äù Gratia smirks. ‚ÄúI was asked to do something in exchange for a reward. But still: I *didn‚Äôt* kill your buddy.‚Äù

‚ÄúThis is a half-assed confession.‚Äù Bern lowers his weapon and just kicks her in the gut. Gratia remains lying down on the ground in pain.

messages.content:
Gratia retches. "...D-Doesn't matter anymore. I failed, and I'm definitely not making it out of this one alive." She lifts herself up slightly to look at Bern. "But still... man, you really are an idiot."

"Shut up." Bern ponders how to hit her next.

"I stabbed him... disrupted his system or whatever, but you're the one who went and ripped his soul out. You killed him, Bern! Good job!" Gratia cackles.

"That's-- that's a lie. You're lying. That's not how that works."

"Wh--ehaha--what would I have to gain from that? It's the fuckin' truth! You incompetent fooooool!! I can't believe you actually--"

Bern tackles her and begins hitting her repeatedly.

messages.content: Theseus makes the active, conscious choice to let the thing that is currently happening continue to happen. They stare woodenly at Gratia's jerking, convulsing form, and remember why they're here. Bern is supposed to be better than this, isn't he? These acts of stupid and selfish violence. But, if it'll make him feel better.. patch up some of the brokenness in his face... Theseus can let it happen. If this will seal the deal between them, make this tentative dance of half-romantic overtures something solid and corporal, Theseus has no choice but to let it happen.

messages.content:
It happens some more.

Bern catches his breath, letting up briefly. "W...what's your *fucking* problem? You shrill... insufferable... lunatic... Is--Is this what she's like in my body?!"

Gratia spits up blood. She's still able to speak, conveniently. "I'm not quite as artful... but she's sorta like me... understands what you don't."

"What is it? Go ahead. Let me know what I don't *understand*!" Bern wraps his hands around her throat.

"...That the only thing to matter is power. You were right to make use of the big guy, sure! Attachments can be helpful. But you let your guard down. Now you're on your own. Just a scrawny little bitch."

Bern begins choking her out. Gratia makes unpleasant gagging noises.

They say quietly, still watching what's in front of them with a sort of perverse fascination. It's.. wrong for Bern to be doing this, isn't it? It's wrong for these hands that Theseus was just holding to be wringing the life from this woman inch by inch. But Bern wants to be *real*. Theseus can make that concession.

This is - they've won, them and Bern, this is *revenge*, what Theseus's wanted from the very beginning! Theseus lets a smile creep over their lips. "He's *not* alone. He has me. But you, Gratia? You're *nothing*. Less than nothing... a pathetic nihilist who's going to choke on her own blood."

"...Lucky. All it was. You caught me off guard with a fluke. By chaaance. An my ally wasn't round. Imthe better..." Gratia mutters, slurred from both delirium and facial injury.
